t to check validity\\ntranscript, err := geminicli.ParseTranscript(data)\\nif err == nil && transcript != nil && len(transcript.Messages) > 0 {\\n    // Parse #2 - inside this function\\n    return geminicli.CalculateTokenUsage(data, startOffset)\\n}\\n```\\n\\nThe same double-parse pattern exists in `countTranscriptItems` (line 372) and `extractUserPrompts` (line 401). Every call to these three functions during condensation parses the Gemini JSON up to 6 times total. Not a correctness issue, but worth noting for future optimization.\\n\\n**2. `getLastPrompt` always passes 0 for startOffset — side effect on token calculation (low)**\\n\\n`manual_commit_hooks.go:1353` — Passing `0` means `calculateTokenUsage` computes tokens for the _entire_ transcript, not just the current checkpoint. This is fine today because `getLastPrompt` only uses the `Prompts` field and ignores `TokenUsage`. But `extractSessionData` still does the calculation, burning cycles. A minor concern — the real risk is if someone later reads `sessionData.TokenUsage` from this call path and gets incorrect values.\\n\\n**3. Test uses `t.Chdir()` without noting the `t.Parallel()` exception (low)**\\n\\nBoth new tests (`TestCondenseSession_GeminiTranscript` at line 468 and `TestCondenseSession_GeminiMultiCheckpoint` at line 620) correctly use `t.Chdir()` and correctly omit `t.Parallel()`. However, per project CLAUDE.md convention, a brief comment explaining why `t.Parallel()` is absent would help future contributors. The existing tests in this file follow the same pattern though, so this is consistent.\\n\\n**4. Removed test coverage for edge cases (low)**\\n\\nThe old `TestExtractUserPromptsFromGeminiJSON` had cases for:\\n- `\\\"user message with empty content\\\"` (empty + valid prompt mixed)\\n- `\\\"invalid JSON\\\"` \\n- `\\\"mixed message types\\\"` with `toolCalls` and `sessionId` fields\\n\\nThese were dropped in the test rewrite. The new `TestExtractUserPrompts` delegates to `geminicli.ExtractAllUserPrompts` which may cover these internally, but the strategy-layer tests no longer exercise these edge cases directly.\\n\\n### Strengths\\n\\n- **Core fix is correct**: Threading `CheckpointTranscriptStart` through to `calculateTokenUsage` and using it as a message index for Gemini (vs line offset for Claude) is the right approach.\\n- **Clean refactoring**: The three format-aware helpers (`countTranscriptItems`, `extractUserPrompts`, `calculateTokenUsage`) with the consistent `AgentTypeGemini || AgentTypeUnknown` pattern are well-structured and follow a uniform fallback strategy.\\n- **Gemini transcript slicing guard**: The comment block at lines 148-153 clearly explains why `SliceFromLine` doesn't work for Gemini JSON, and the decision to pass the full transcript to the summarizer is correct (even if it means Gemini summaries won't be scoped per-checkpoint — the alternative is malformed JSON).\\n- **Multi-checkpoint test** (`TestCondenseSession_GeminiMultiCheckpoint`): This is thorough — it simulates a real two-checkpoint session, manually sets `CheckpointTranscriptStart = 2`, and verifies that only the second gemini message's tokens (200/75/30) are counted, not the first (100/50/20). This directly validates the bug fix.\\n- **Comment updates**: Old references to `entire/sessions` branch corrected to `entire/checkpoints/v1`.\\n\\n### Summary\\n\\nThe PR correctly fixes the core bug — Gemini token usage is now scoped per-checkpoint rather than cumulative. The refactoring is clean and consistent. The double-parse overhead (#1) is the most notable issue but isn't a correctness problem. I'd call this **ready to merge** with the double-parse as a follow-up optimization task.\"}],\"stop_reason\":null,\"stop_sequence\":null,\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":1,\"cache_creation_input_tokens\":1734,\"cache_read_input_tokens\":71995,\"cache_creation\":{\"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens\":0,\"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens\":1734},\"output_tokens\":1,\"service_tier\":\"standard\",\"infer